The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria: in total they have 29%
The perceptible weakening of both existing parties in the grand coalition and this marked strengthening of right-wing populist parties led, according to the first provisional results, to early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), within which the position of the current president Wilhelm Molterer is seriously faltering, has suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the contrary, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Kärnten sub-prefect Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to provisional results, the strongest party in the country remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8% of the vote, but it loses 5.5% compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was for the ÖVP, which lost almost 9% of the vote with 25.6%.
These are the worst results of these two great parties in post-war Austrian history and above all the literally catastrophic result of the People's Party, which provoked early elections.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable advantage in the preferences ahead of the SPÖ.
But voters evidently punished them for sinking the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party president, Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Monterer.
Observers believe that it could take place as early as Monday during the extraordinary convocation of the party leadership.
This development should perhaps facilitate the path towards the increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. towards the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
Regarding the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the liberals (FPÖ) gained 18% early and the BZÖ 11% of the vote - but the Social Democrats simultaneously revealed the concern of another 1999, when the populists agreed with the popular to the collective government, (then the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it separated from the BZÖ) which was even a reason for sanctions by the European Union.
Haider is evidently playing on this development, having already declared that he is ready to collaborate with any party and presumes a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Green Party also managed to enter the Parliament, but fell slightly, falling from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has evidently exceeded the 4% threshold and has not entered Parliament.
Duel to the death: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
From this it is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Despite this, there are many reasons to get a self-reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to the latest album by Maxim Turbulenc.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LPs and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
But if on your shelves are crowded vinyls of hard-rock, jazz or blues probably, such a turntable at least you dream of it.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here too there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the twenty-crown headphones on the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life decides.
Some high-quality music players can do more than just read music, which phones don't even accidentally.
There is no other device as universal today as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, phone calls and text messages, can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even browse.
And if we take into account smartphones and PDAs you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle since no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the mobile phone and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few mobile phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, do not count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add a few calls from time to time, get another charger at work for safety, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you will not have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours with continuous functionality with a charge.
A further problem exists when downloading music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to cope without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with some exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create their own media library sorted by performers' names, album name, genre or user classification.
Some devices only mimic the folder tree, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you are especially interested in battery strength, memory capacity, the quality and type of audio outputs and, of course, ease of use.
If you need music mainly as background music and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you just need any mobile phone that reads MP3.
This is now, clearly true of any mobile phone.
You don't have to worry too much about which formats your phone or player recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format, which belongs to the most popular ones, the majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by the Apple company and its Ipod).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile phone-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
Prices are not really very low.
But it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile phones with them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little bit rummage through your pocket while your MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile phone readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than 3 thousand crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very decent walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for common headphones.
The best and technically more equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
Instead, the advantage of readers is, among others, easy handling.
The simplest ones not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) can really anyone handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping into the start of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
Which appliance to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (such as M2, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, which are included in the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones make it even with 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and also want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners preferably take specialized mobiles - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual buttons for MP3 and the convenience of the service thus approaches the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has come a long way in this area, as mobile phones in the Walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and price category up to 4 000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Perhaps it will not be missing for a long time.
We have already written about the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive ones in Europe many times on Mobil.cz.
After all, this was also confirmed by ČTÚ, pointing out that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's latest steps in the field of regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high vis-à-vis Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the clash.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage well above 100 %.
Mobile telophony operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably no longer has many possibilities. (After all, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility – the virtual operator.
The entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant drop in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices were ringing out in Britain.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, we don't have to go very far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to actually work, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, that is to say, relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators are usually at low cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the narrower service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that costs at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a bet on a target group can also be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men, so to speak.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz, CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small due to a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Plus, from a service point of view, it's relatively saturated."
No chance in Czech Republic, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever to be an operator in the Czech Republic, Mobilking will not be.
"There is talk of expanding this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have many expectations.
The lighting of Mobilking will rather take place in the other countries in our area," Jana Studničková, the press spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation for Mobile.cz.
Thus he indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thinking.
Rather, on the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them," says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
From unofficial information it emerges that we will have to have the first virtual operator perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, an impenetrable wall of silence stands around its creation.
"Right now we don't believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now, no person with a complex and serious project has approached us," Vlastimil Sršeň of Telefònika O2's press section mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial commercial project on which we can continue to build."
He adds: "A virtual operator is unlikely to appear in the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this moment we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its 3G license demands.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
The competent authorities - with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation U:fon testify that when operators care about one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing on ČTÚ at the time of the creation of U:fon towards the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by the information publicly accessible from the ČTÚ web pages.
But now U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has just been strengthened with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services."
However, the attitude of mobile telephone operators is quite surprising in the complete disinterest of Czech regulators.
It is not just a question of the attitude of the ČTÚ which, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer from potential buyers has probably not been attractive enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS External Relations Section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
On the other hand, on the part of the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and, moreover, to ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators commonly work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the lowering of prices for mobile phone services."
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises by itself.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and the fight against competition.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking in the telecoms regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many points of contention.
Of course, there is the analysis of relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the agreement of the network operator is always required for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – logically at the end of the day – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for ÚOHS it should be a minimum alert that three mobile operators proceed in such an eerily similar way.
At the same time complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all traders they encounter very similar obstacles.
Shifting responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps out of the whole thing.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve from this.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this fact more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done, when no one is watching
While without us noticing it, the operation of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
Usually these are companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only predetermined people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator is a classic corporate customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As an important customer then receives offers of special prices (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about, which we will look into, arise, it could be a violation of contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," Martina Kemrová replied to the question in question.
But it is highly unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time against such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a considerable profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot dispose of it in full like regular customers of mobile operators."
But this should be a little strange at ČTÚ.
In addition, another question opens up for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to it it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we will no longer be expensive
As has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile telephony market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the operators were born, the traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, at least too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries, it is precisely in these cases that regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then the first virtual operator was created and others joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw themselves from one to the other like a hot potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of competences in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let us not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator really soon appears with us, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS could hardly remain impassive to the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj" on the occasion of the Day of Recognition of the Czech State.
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, chorus step and instrumental edition.
The singing is conducted by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the hymn are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz website you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful anthems.
Already earlier he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the solo variants, singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to make sure that both and also the choir, have clear diction, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year the 175^ anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
