On Wednesday MHD Prague will accompany you for the first time with an electronic card
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, tramway and bus instead of the paper ticket with an electronic card in their pocket.
Right now about one hundred thousand people who have their own Opencard can get it.
Passengers can buy the 30- and 90-day and annual metro station (which will be valid from the first of January 2009) and at the same time have their card recharged at the Infopoints and offices of the Transport Company and at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons can be purchased since yesterday on the internet at the page of the Compagnia dei Trasporti www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred customers took advantage of the service before the afternoon.
Those who start using the internet service can completely forget about the counters in the metro stops where until now they had to queue for paper tickets.
The coupon can be purchased via the internet and on the Opencard they recharge it on one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places, passengers have access to a counter with trained staff who will help those interested in purchasing on the internet and will also record the credit acquired on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to load electronic coupons on Opencards in ATMs and self-service that are installed at the metro entrances.
