Sudeten Germans in 1945 demanded to include Šumava in the United States.
This is apparent from the letter deposited in the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, some groups of Sudeten Germans reportedly turned to the president of the United States in 1945.
This is also apparent from the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the American president not to allow again the return of the "district of Šumava" – occupied by Hitler under the Munich agreement – to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and we want to be sure of the promises that American units will come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads the letter signed with the words "The people who care about the fate of Šumava with all their hearts."
Since, they say, the annexation to Czechoslovakia – knowing the Czech national character – gives Sudeten Germans hope only to brutality, lack of regard, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter beg the American president to assume the control over Shumava now and always.
"We cannot believe that without regard for the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would recognize this territory as a state alien to us, which oppresses and eradicates ethnic minorities and has contributed nothing or nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign it is the alleged fear of the thirst for revenge on the part of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States were to doubt the conviction of the Germans of Šumava, it would be enough to organize a referendum in the district on the willingness of its inhabitants to become part of the USA or to live under the mastery of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may seem naïve with our knowledge of post-war history, according to some witnesses it aptly describes the expectations of Sudeten Germans at the time.
Although the Czech Germans had to guess that it would be their displacement from the republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility altogether.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate some sort of autonomy for the Sudeten peoples.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was mobilized during the war as a Budějovice German in the Baltic Sea maritime power.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in the prison camp in Holštýn, dozens of other Czech Germans visited him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that when they got home, the Czech would suit them," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war were counting on the Beneš decrees to be moved from the Republic.
