1. Even rats have feelings
A rat or cockroach flees when they feel danger. Does it mean that they also feel fear?
Neurologist scientist Joseph Le Doux is convinced: many animals also have feelings.
4. But how could we verify if, when they behave in the same way as us, they have the same sensations as us?
In the Internet newspaper "Edge" for some years now articles by well-known scientists have been published.
6. SPIEGEL ONLINE in a series presents selected answers to the question: "What do you believe to be true, without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings or other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far, since we cannot even prove that other men have consciousness.
But in this case we must at least hope, that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
9. As soon as we turn to other species and ask questions about feeling or consciousness in general, we enter impassable territory, because the reference base does not match.
When a rat is in a dangerous situation, it does the same things that other animals do. That is, he pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from where some scientists understand that there is a comparable subjective feeling.
I don't believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult for us to convey our feelings towards animals.
On the one hand, the lateral prefrontal cortex is often connected with human awareness, the associated circuits (this is due to its direct participation in short memory and executive and control functions).
In man this large area is much more developed than in other primates and it seems that among other creatures it is completely lacking.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness dependent on the prefrontal cortex, including knowledge, who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, the assumption that humans differ even from other primates is thus admitted.
Another dramatic peculiarity should occur in man's way of speaking: since a large part of life is connected to language, it is often said to be linked to consciousness.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
Although awareness does not depend on language, it would influence it so that the awareness of the animal, as it is made, certainly differs greatly from the circumstances of our consciousness.
For this reason, it is difficult to discover how consciousness can be seen in other animals.
If it is not possible to measure it as an internal and subjective thing, in analyzing it through one's own experience because of the special hardware, their research will pose great problems for us.
Most interpretations refer to the content of conscious experience, but apart from that there is another aspect of consciousness that would be easier for science to access.
One could analyze the processes of animal consciousness without regard to their contents, and this is precisely what happens in studies on the short memory of primates , in particular to the example of visualization.
So for this principle, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick follow, we pass first to the neural correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: both could be identical but not necessarily.
In an interesting way this principle also highlights the value of the prefrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
So what is outlined for feelings?
I attribute them to the fact that an emotional system such as fear is activated in one of its conscious brain activities.
What we refer to as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) occupies the working memory.
Seen in this way, the feelings are closely connected to the regions of the cortex, which characterize the primates and in particular the human being.
With the speaking nature subtle nuances of feeling are created, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize situations, to describe them to others.
For example, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings result from more primitive body regions' activities of cortex and paleocephalus sensations, similar to Jack Pankseep, who however focused more on paleocephalus.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, this could absolutely be part of the feelings extended to the species.
On a purely theoretical level I cannot contradict it, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep makes arguments that what appears to rats and humans as fear is probably felt so with the senses in both cases: but how could this occur, if rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
Does a cockroach in case of danger flee as if it also felt fear?
In my eyes the mere similarity of behavior cannot yet demonstrate any vital similarity.
And that is, neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar paleoencephalians, cockroaches not even a brain.
But is the paleoencephalon responsible for feelings?
And even if you could prove it for human beings: how is it that you would want to prove it on rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even insects (who knows?), have feelings.
But I didn't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on specific circuits and language), I prefer to study emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there are advances here at the neural level, as long as the same procedure is given up on rats and humans.
Just as I don't research language and consciousness in rats, I don't do research on their emotions, I don't even know if they exist.
This may be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to take steps forward, rather than constantly hit a wall.
I am precisely a practical emotional.
