Dark matter influences the flight of space probes
For years, a mysterious phenomenon has been creating perplexity among scientists: dark matter influences the speed of space probes during the so-called Swing-by maneuver.
Experts fear that Albert Einsteins' general theory of relativity may not be entirely accurate.
The Ulysses space probe has been flying through space for nearly 18 years.
Because of the fast freezing fuel lines, death by freezing now hangs over her.
Among scientists for years a mysterious phenomenon has been creating havoc – the anomaly of the Swing-by
The Swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes, with which they obtain additional momentum / thrust / oscillation in the gravitational field of a celestial body, for example of the Earth.
So the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The Euro-American Cassini-Huygens research probe used this physical gimmick as well as the Ulysses solar probe.
What has amazed scholars for years: rockets do not behave at all as one would expect according to the law of gravitation.
On the contrary, it comes to irregularities in speed.
The probes suddenly become faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
The year renamed the Swing-by anomaly.
Some experts fear that perhaps even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the force of attraction of matter with a curvature of space, may not be entirely accurate.
The American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton firmly believes that before Einstein was not wrong, and attempts to explain the anomaly of the Swing-by by means of the so-called dark matter that astronomers have spotted in the cosmos.
"Responsible for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to Earth," he writes.
Space scientists have only known about the existence of dark matter for about 10 years.
From her evidently comes a force of attraction, whose effect on the other celestial bodies is visible.
She herself is completely invisible, i.e. she does not send or reflect any electromagnetic radiation whatsoever, especially any visible light.
According to scientists' calculations, dark matter makes up at least a good fifth of the entire mass of the cosmos.
