Turkey is broadening diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
That's at least what the tour guides tell you.
The building straddles between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial town halls.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the magnitude of the enterprise of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a laggard to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and dominating forces advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station too.
In 1917 an ammunition train burst destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly decayed, largely overtaken by history.
But nowadays, this railway outlet to Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-widening diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car to the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a jolt ride along the tracks that produced the ancient world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and steel facility - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and power pastry shops, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make contracts early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it must look east and west at the same time.
That was not the case with one or the other.
They have to be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "Turkey will be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want where to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has recited from memory: the ties of the not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, The whole of Europe can metaphorically travel those railway lines eastward through Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another blank night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions can now, in large part, be in Turkey's hands.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
Then at least there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent should lay claim to this fascinating country.
