Dark city streets, often forgotten and perhaps soon for sale
New York City has thousands of avenues, boulevards, streets and other side streets, some famous, others merely of use.
But also many veteran taxi drivers and long-time residents find it difficult to give the location of Extra Place, mostly because they have never heard of it.
The tiny street is in the East Village and runs north from First Street – without making Second Street – between Bowery and Second Avenue.
About 30 feet wide and 120 feet long, it looks more like a dusty alley than an active busy street.
There are no road signs.
It is virtually impossible to see it on a normal atlas.
The road must, however, have admirers.
For example, there's Avalon Bay, the real estate company of the newly built luxury buildings on First Street.
They want to reopen Extra Place and create a cleaner passage for shops and boutiques that are expected to open in new buildings.
Other admirers include longtime neighbors who say they were hit by the truncated road simply because it was one of the last remnants of the stately neighborhood of the past.
But the city's preservation and development department, which has control of the streets, has no interest in keeping it.
During a meeting of the land use committee of the district municipal commission some representatives of the city agency and Avalon Bay outlined a proposal for the real estate company to buy the streets.
But the committee prefers the street to remain in the hands of the city, and has called for a new plan to be presented next month, says Susan Stetzer, the district director of Community Board 3.
"There is very little space left to the city property, and we would like the city to continue to own Extra Place," he said.
"There could be proposals to fix and manage it, which could be done by Avalon, but we also want to ensure public access."
Avalon Bay announced many months ago that it would reopen the small street and install seating, including some to use for a café to which the real estate company hopes to rent the space.
The idea of Avalon Bay buying the road was first made public at this month's meeting.
Michele de Milly, a spokesman for Avalon Bay, said that although the company wants to use the road, it doesn't necessarily mean it wants to own it.
"Avalon Bay's main concern is to renovate this derelict alley and turn it into a public amenity," he said, adding that the city suggested the sale.
Seth Donlin, a spokesman for Housing Preservation, said it was the city's desire to sell the street and noted that the agency's purpose was to develop the property rather than administer it.
In comparison to its more colorful neighbor, Bowery, Extra Place has left a slight historical imprint.
Some believe it got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided among his many sons and the narrow strip of land was not claimed.
The back door of CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened on Extra Place, and the street is perhaps best known as the set for the Ramones album cover photo "Rocket to Russia."
"The ground was beautiful," said Danny Fields, the Ramones' manager, who took the picture in November 1976.
"It was full of garbage, shreds of clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves, ropes."
Some residents, including some bloggers writing about "gentrification" of the East Village, have opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the piece of public property, modest as it is, should remain public.
Others praised Extra Place as a rarity — a snippet of city hardly changed at all that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who has a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Lamentations: A Somewhat Nostalgic Look at the Endangered City"), published part of a Discourse on the City's History that appeared in The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow cul-de-sac, dark even by day and bordered rusty-iron warehouse doors and shuttered windows, with weeks-old newspapers fluttering along the slums."
With a few exceptions, the street looked almost the same as a recent evening.
A rat ran nimbly across the back of the street near a door leading into the CBGB, which is now the site of an aristocratic clothing store.
On the walls were graffiti and an empty 22-ounce beer bottle lies next to a cluster of fresh abandoned newspapers.
Few passers-by said they rarely thought of Extra Place but suggested it would need to be graced a bit.
Mr. Fields, for his part, said he also thinks some people underestimate the attraction of the road in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in black, dirty, disgusting places."
The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior fellow in California Studies and the senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School."
Truly attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama's educational projects are a case in point.
Mr. Obama's campaign notes that, "African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students," which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving goals, Obama's education plan specifically advocates, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for English learners.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching languages other than English in the classroom, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The school's students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth-graders, an astounding 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 state math exam.
An equally astounding 93 percent of fourth-graders took the proficient-level test on English-language.
This incredible result was achieved by using a different ingredient from Mr. Obama's preferred one.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and practice, constant assessment of skills, and a "no excuses" attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school's obstructive approach for English learners is "full immersion."
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We had fantastic success with a student who had just come from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you would not have been able to identify what it was."
"It works," he noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model and replicate it in other schools with a Hispanic majority and English students?
The school's achievements make answering that question very easy, but education policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a longtime advocate for bilingual education) and its own ongoing support for bilingual education prevent predicting Mr. Obama's response.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the topic corny when he said people should stop worrying about "English-only" legislation.
Instead, he said, "you have to make sure your children are able to speak Spanish."
If Obama truly wishes to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despising or trivializing them.
