Gebrselassie rested breaks his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia showed again why many consider him the best marathon runner ever, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile run under 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a favorably flat race victory in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shattered by 27 seconds his previous score of 2:03:26, run last year in Berlin.
At 35, Gebrselassie set the 26th world record in a career so stunning that it produced a world championship or world record at every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing — perhaps too alarmingly, in retrospect — that air pollution would worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he decided to run in Berlin.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at the start, 55 degrees at the finish - Gebrselassie won Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As soon as half cross-country skiers like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya have gone long distances, the marathon record has fallen by more than two minutes in the past decades, since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had cramps in his calves and missed a week of training.
