She ran a race doing the calculations well, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners start with a large gap, resuming them after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Tucked away in the theme park sprawling over the suburbs of Orlando, just a few miles from the splendor, noise, and enormousness, lies the tranquil city where pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first incorporated all-black town in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the town of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools, and no prisons."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, the most famous writer of Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city he described — and that makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project — remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the thirties, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little about us, he doesn't know what's being lost."
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called in for a keynote address on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very cautious about how our story is told," said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be fair."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grabbing and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shade of the oaks of the rural culture of southern blacks - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for the Eatonville image really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books such as Mules and Men (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Rout 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida into a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Short as a bass drum in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Off the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trimmings, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the walk-through rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it the way she was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls Hurston captures by quoting men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned to her family who moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston swooped into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today prides itself on decent clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others grinned.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 20s, she was buried in a gravestone without a plaque at Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major memorial ceremonies, and no major conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 80s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the western edge of the city.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the fifties, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white guys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on one side," Mr. Franklin says.
"We actually had a girl who was killed by that once.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say the desegregation of schools, while positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville's cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged — I remember this — you hugged your teacher in the morning, hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there's a cultural divide there," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's plaqueless grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit the shelves of bookstores, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had beamed the limelight again.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its project on the street.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what one would call high speed, a real pride for the city," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's self-image.
Out-of-town people like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the public historical register in 1998.
A new single-story bookstore (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly of Florida: only six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 80s of the 1800s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for Eatonville's history, because of its significance, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most interviews, some things — such as murals on Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a plump teacher with a penchant for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing her entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, no better, no worse and proud, creative, hard-working, foolish and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in local government or for the Police Department, who he said he might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"A lot of people, if they're just coming in here, they're going to think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it's really a pretty city."
Here in New York we all talk fluently about finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan kept away from the newspaper stalls and huge television screens of Times Square, they wouldn't notice they were in the eye of the storm.
They would never guess that the glass offices, honeycombs above their heads the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York live every day the worst "bad day in the office" since the crash of 1929.
Bellhops shake metal tea carts across sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between apartment buildings carrying, like human mules, 50 broken ironed shirts hanging from a stick on their shoulders.
Employees still wait in line for their morning bagels at food carts on the sidewalks, and it's still impossible to take a yellow taxi between 4pm and 7pm on a working day.
It didn't seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the matter to coincide with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier's counter, to withdraw money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "trusted banker," were lining up for the same reason as I did.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken savings from smaller banks from places they commute from, such as those from New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken the money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a construction company), credit unions and types of city savings banks whose branches operate only within a state, and say they treat customers like family members.
In past years, 15 of these banks have failed.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, was placed under receivership, and, as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with savings deposits of $440 billion, was looking for a buyer to bail it out.
The clerks and clerks standing in front of me, fearful of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking Wall Street for more bailouts.
Ordinary New Yorkers have become proficient in finance in recent weeks.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, talking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the failing bank, and its emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed doorkeeper, almost fifty years old from my apartment building, changed the subject from our normal topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
I've changed, I'm not taking any risks."
Lives Remembered: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: as Guildford's Music Director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and choir.
As a member of his scheme of music for the municipality, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
They were supposed to be under-21s/under 21s, but at the time Proteus sang its final in 1979, many of us were in our twenties – we simply refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological changeable being) represented the goodwill of the choir and the ability to deal with everything the music presented to do, whether madrigals or Messiaen, without accompaniment or with the whole orchestra.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often astounding, always exciting, and it was all because of that man's inspiration and enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely constant through the years.
How often we were told by Tod to "let the music speak for itself."
He had said, "The composer knows what he wants.
There's everything there, in the music.
So sing it!"
His technique in the use of the wand was absolutely clear and precise, although never dictatorial or flowery.
Whatever the musical standard, it made it higher and higher.
John Frayn Turner says:
If a conductor were to be knighted, it would be Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he led the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
During the past 40 years and more I have watched more than 100 of his concerts and I can honestly say that I have never disagreed with just one of them - and many times inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his own words, simply "rode around the world one or two well-known warhorses."
He will be missed by so many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25) specifies that "in 1946 he resumed studying economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a researcher at Houblon-Norman... studying at the same time for a degree in science, one in letters and a PhD".
This follows from Woodruff's author's note in Beyond Nab End, but it is incorrect.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a university lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham, at which time he completed a PhD thesis on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor J. D. Chambers, and subsequently published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
He spent 1950-51 in the USA as a researcher at Houblon-Norman, and the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham permanently for Illinois.
Why Woodruff chose to cover this part of his career, it is not known.
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria turns right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, to the left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing Vlaams Belang party, take part in a demonstration to present the organization "Cities Against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry signs like street signs representing mosques with a red line passing in the middle.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties gained heavily in national general elections.
More than 90 graves were badly damaged at the Traun cemetery, near Linz, in a few hours between Friday night and this morning, in what police believe was an organized action.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David over some graves, but detectives believe it may have been an attempt to mask extremist motivations driven by a hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident is related in any way to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which took place towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, embarked on a journey of spiritual research following its turn to the right in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that took almost 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with vehemently anti-immigration tickets, and some of their slogans were called xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the head of the Freedom Party who won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against veils and burkas and also expressed his opposition to foods that are perceived as connected to Islam.
At the final gathering in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties seem to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of a continued Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analysis done immediately after the election, which established the far right as the strongest political bloc in the nation, indicating that the change was being brought about predominantly by young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
Trip abroad forbidden to Gary Glitter.
Gary Glitter, the glamorous rock star guilty of child sexual abuse, was banned from traveling to France and Spain by the court.
Prosecutors imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he informed the authorities who controlled him that he wanted to go to Spain via France.
The ban on travelling abroad was granted to Kent Police last Thursday after it provided prosecutors with evidence of Glitter's previous arrests for child sexual abuse.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadi, was not present at the hearing at the Ashford District Court in Kent but was represented by Corker Binning's lawyers.
A spokesman for the Court Service said: "On Thursday 25 September at the Ashford District Court, Kent Police made a request to prevent Mr Paul Gadd's overseas travel to France and Spain until 25 March.
"Paul Gadd was not present in person."
Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad as required by the register of convicted sex offenders.
He must notify the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He is also required to give the police seven days' notice of his scheduled departure date.
Failure to notify the authorities can lead to a sentence of five years in prison.
Kent Police said they would not discuss individual cases or possible movements of Glitter in the country.
A spokesman for Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do whatever it takes to protect children in this country or abroad.
"From our perspective, it is easier to monitor someone who remains in the UK because we have comprehensive systems in place to manage any potential risk more effectively.
"Protecting Kent residents is the primary concern of Kent Police and we work closely to monitor the behaviour of convicted sex offenders registered in the country to minimise any possible risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls aged 10 and 11.
When Glitter came he flew to Bangkok where he was supposed to board a flight to London.
But he said he felt ill and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities would not pass him through passport control and eventually took a flight to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also did not let him in and he returned to Bangkok where Thai police and immigration officials insisted that he return to England.
He eventually arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to the Uxbridge District Court, west London, since Scotland Yard had successfully applied for an order to put him on the register of sex offenders.
Glitter was previously jailed in the UK in 1999 for possessing child abuse images.
An Interior Ministry source said Jacqui Smith, the interior secretary, felt reassured and happy that Glitter had been stopped from travelling to France and Spain.
"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
Neither heels nor ruffles nor dresses from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in private, in those moments far from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen gaze or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the less known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day more and more," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" it could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and to capture the audience.
To capture the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
Because their personality and character are internal.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of flamenco greats with the camera."
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, resemble classic photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's conception of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not dancing, singing or playing in itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, figure in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love portraying people, getting to know them and being able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, be it a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare yourself with people, characters that sometimes you don't even know or who only give you a few minutes to take the picture.
Beyond these circumstances, like a photographer, I always try to concretize my ideas."
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 of via de la Mata, parallel to Alameda de Hercules street, and will be open to the public until next October 16th.
Vargas Llosa reveals that the novel he is writing is a "gamble"
It is set in places he does not yet know and deals with unknown topics: despite this, Mario Vargas Llosa is struggling with a new project he is working on, a novel whose protagonist, Roger Casemant, is an Irish nationalist who lived twenty years in Congo and crossed the Amazon.
Always a favorite for the Nobel Prize for Literature, the writer confessed yesterday on the occasion of the Hay Festival in Segovia, that the project he is dealing with today "is a gamble" and that "everything indicates that I should not write it."
"If I had common sense, I would not write it, but I will do it anyway and I hope to finish it as soon as possible," he concluded his speech at the festival for the exchange of ideas, thoughts and words that for four days saw a hundred writers, historians, journalists and thousands of people pass through the city of the Aqueduct.
The author of "La ciudad y los perros" was, as expected, the leading figure at the third edition of the festival of the word.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival award for being the most voted writer by the participants – an ancient edition of Dickens' book "Our mutual friend", filled the seats of the Juan Bravo theater.
Presented by Félix Romeo, the writer found himself in front of an audience to which time flew when the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and with large doses of humor, recalled how the literary vocation was born in him, derived from the "extraordinary adventure" of the "pleasure of reading" and "living beyond what I lived"; as he writes in "a disciplined way" to make up for the "lack of inspiration", with an intense work of documentation, drafting and continuous remaking; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his vocation and how "the images of memory" are the basis on which his stories rest.
The Hispanic-American novelist acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and know whether books can change people's lives, "but I refuse to believe that literature is pure entertainment, an ephemeral experience," Vargas Llosa pointed out, arguing that, on the contrary, it "has effects" and that it "makes people more nonconformist." For this reason, he invited writers to "not give in to frivolity" and to "take responsibility" for their vocation.
