"Sangre de mayo", Garci's epic bet
Inspired by Episodios Nacionales by Benito Pérez Galdós, Jose Luis Garci re-proposes in Sangre de mayo the famous revolt of the Spaniards against the French, in what is the most ambitious film of his filmography, with almost 15 million euros of budget.
With this film, the director attempted to "illustrate the torrent of characters and at the same time the social analysis" that he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutierrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of a large cast of performers.
Sangre de mayo, more than two and a half hours long, debuts this Friday in cinemas, to become in the future a television miniseries of more than four hours on TeleMadrid.
A great admirer of Galdós' literature, Jose Luis Garci claims to have realized with this shot "a dream of his childhood", and believes he must thank Esperanza Aguirre, who had commissioned him from the Community of Madrid three years before shooting a commemorative film for the second centenary of May 2 medrilegno. The director had agreed on the condition that the story was based on the novel Episodios Nacionales.
The 15 million budgets allocated in full by the Community of Madrid represented for Garci a "unique opportunity" to recreate the appropriate sets and costumes to portray a "stunned Spain that mischose the leader to fight for and the fact that the struggle for independence brought the people a huge delay in development under the reign of Ferdinand VII", Garci noted.
However, the director regrets that he did not receive funding equal to those of Alatriste or Los fantasmas de Goya - more than double that of Sangre de mayo, so it was not possible to shoot some scenes planned by the set design that he himself had signed together with Horacio Valcarcel, collaborator of almost his entire career.
This, for the director of Volver a empezar, has influenced what is his usual work practice, the staging with the actors, with whom he often rehearses before shooting together with those who will not be part of the cast, because he considers it "humiliating," considering that "part of the director's job lies in going to the theater and cinema to know what is happening in the sector in which he works."
Many of the performers, some of whom are part of the cast of Sangre de mayo, rehearse in front of his car, as in the case of Michael Rell, Carlos Larranaga or Fernando Guillen Cuervo.
A four-time Oscar nominee — winning one — Garci believes that none of the three films nominated to represent Spain at the Hollywood Academy this year — his Sangre de mayo, Siete mesas de billar francés and, the latest selected Los girasoles ciegos — do not represent the younger generation of Spanish cinema "that should instead be known."
Garci does not expect any awards from this film.
"At first you think you're working for posterity, then you realize that you only work for prosperity, and at some point you conform to just making one more film," Garci explains after more than 30 years of career.
Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sevillian essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer pays tribute to another dancer also from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Firenze Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a free dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of women's emancipation, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, which marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in interwar Europe, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. It seemed incredible."
The dancer says: "we do not pretend to tell her whole life, but to collect its spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested to me some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "la danza de la mariposa" suggested me a guajira, or "la danza de la serpiente" some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing is also part of this aesthetic," she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as he did in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been one of her students.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy because he has agreed to work in my work and I feel very honored for this."
The staging also includes musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, singing by Miguel Ortega, Pulga y Moi by Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal accompanist of these artists who have been all-round divas, and who have always had many suitors."
In the work there is also in some form the life of this woman that takes place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since, usually, she resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her, because I think she is one of the women who had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her and even less considers her work as something of value," says Bayon.
The show will start today, at 20.30 at the theater of Lope de Vega.
