The "ape car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking as an example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers from the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer's vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to Nissan's safety shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of bees, able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers developed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
This mechanism identifies the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents the collision.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right or greater angles to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
'If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, or even diagonally; It can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and not taking advantage of infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require the memorization of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
It is the first step towards developing new technologies for instant collision avoidance, a technology that Nissan hopes will come standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to get the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles in the path.
Drivers who repeat alcoholism will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol levels, install in his car the system that prevents driving the vehicle while intoxicated or if you do not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General's Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The aim of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
In addition to the General Prosecutor's Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Technological Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for drink-driving then return to driving the car.
The alcolock would avoid this, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce up to 65% of infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviors before they become criminal offenses.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, no doubt the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced on an experimental basis in some commercial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the PSOE in which it proposes to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
