Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, at most it gets scared, but it doesn't really really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It occurs with some frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadic (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, bedwetting (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with stages of very high fever, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, shouts, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What you can do, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite the baby before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
Once the somniloquies appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if you appear very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to interrogate him to get information.
You will not achieve anything, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thinking.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not to see what he is dreaming to say it, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it could lead.
Never tell the child that you might ask him questions during the night to learn his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
