The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday's tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the trust of the public, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 80s.
Faced with such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drafting a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started operations, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continuous efforts to improve blood sample safety and field research over the following years, we have regained the trust of the public," she explains before proudly stating that by early 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has chaired it since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when there are doubts and a serious illness could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which manifests itself as a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusionary measures are adopted.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for some years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests, which allow the presence of the virus to be recognized directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to reduce the window period, i.e. from the moment in which the person has contracted the disease to that in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have considerably reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion is detected.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Héma-Québec directorate.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
As recently as a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"The needs increase as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average make up only 3% of Quebecers acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are at least 18 years old and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of donors are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor group need to be renewed as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that you find hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary, desolate.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissue, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is an abundance of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the inclusion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to withdraw more than a thousand each year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
