Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice-president director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million libel suit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house with the intention of starting a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to hers.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a large sum of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these struggles with unequal weapons, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gags the opposition as well as frightening anyone who dares to pronounce himself again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in front of the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates usually take place with the exchange of views and not with batons.
It would therefore have been sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much trust in public opinion and badly rejects the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is evident?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the lawyers handsomely paid and not the whole of Canadians ; Here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn't understand – or doesn't want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Nero does so primarily because it rejects the mining's brutal means.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of gag (seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum ordering them to stop using that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal speech, Barrack Gold's lawsuit constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies en bloc the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics uncomfortable to the richest companies in the world, under penalty of multiple lawsuits, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific norms as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right of reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the academic world, as is the same public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
Operation - rescue for Wall Street - Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic camps, yesterday finally came to an agreement on the biggest financial rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has been weighing on Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular: checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to limit the number of houses foreclosed for non-payment, as well as a right of inspection on the salaries paid to the managers of protected companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on the markets," said Bush administration Representative Henry Paulson.
"Every decision was made in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the crux of the matter: If we hadn't done this, priceless discomfort and turmoil would have spilled over into the daily lives of Americans," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
Later in the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential elections were rather supportive of the agreement, without however avoiding expressing their discontent with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves credit for adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow owners to keep their domicile and the one concerning the salaries for managers of state-covered companies.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American TV screen.
Asked on another channel to see if he would vote for the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"According to what I've read, it's something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (mortgages), then extended to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of liquidity and the lurch of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans who threw up the first draft of a deal last week.
We seem to have come out of that impasse since the Democrats have accepted that the "toxic" assets of some struggling companies are only protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to accommodate everyone, a provision has been added to Congress that if the government were to face losses over the next five years as a result of this program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of an initial sum of 250 billion to which another 100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The $350 billion payment would have to be ratified by a further vote in Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will get shares in protected companies that will be worth dividends in case of profit and that it can sell when the dust settles.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the possibility to delay foreclosure procedures relating to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and starting allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the plan's architects would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives, and a vote in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is still not certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
"Evidently, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But certainly not to take advantage of taxpayers.
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and to carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we were once again witnessing the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNS Paribas announced that it would give up the purchase of its competitor, which was in full bankruptcy after the loss of 2 billion euros ($ 2.9 billion) due to the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis has 85,000 employees and is one of the twenty largest banks in Europe and the ten largest insurers.
"It's not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, they gain influence and voting rights in banking matters.
It is certainly something that savers and households appreciate now that times are uncertain."
During this period, at the other end of the Channel, the British government seems to be on the verge of nationalizing another bank teetering in the balance of the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take charge of all the loans currently in progress at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) in real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the British government.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
The blue-eyed beauty was for a long time her trump card, for others her weak point.
Had he gotten rid of the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the bewitching smile?
Yes and no.
His discretion, sensitivity and evident talent would have expelled him from that circle of powerful consecrated to real sacred monsters.
But what a constancy!
Paul Newman, who died Friday, at the age of 83, at his ranch in Connecticut, following lung cancer, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the heyday.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on the screen, more prudent in his game, certainly more fragile, but also a spokesman for freedom and the development of dramatic convictions.
Magical children are often born from mixed couples.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
A humble ego, ultimate mark of quality.
Since in him you recognized a whole country in love with the safe made man, the fighter of the Pacific war, proud in combat, who at the beginning of the 50s studied dramatic art at Yale, he later attended the Actor Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, television and soon in the cinema.
That same civil rights activist was also the race car driver who finished second at the 24 Hours of Mans in 1979, as well as a sex symbol, although part of a model couple from 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
The gray areas of a reserved, discreet, committed star, allergic to show-business scandals, of which it will never be possible to completely reveal the mystery, go with him.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
This weekend the passing of Paul Newman was a blast to the heart for cinephiles, while his great characters populate the black screen of memories.
Over half a century of American cinema in full transformation is revived through his interpretations.
Butch Cassidy's charming cowboy (1969) and that boy unable to desire his fiery wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Tennessee Williams' 1958 Burning Cat are confused in the memory.
More recently, we remember him as the sensitive Mr. Bridge (1990), troubled by a marriage that did not keep what he promised.
Many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
The boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Up There Someone Loves Me, by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean and revived after his death, which officially launched Newman in 1956.
That nice thug in the excellent Stangata, Oscar for best film in 1973.
Bitter and vindictive billiard player in The Scoundrel, a magnificent film by Robert Rossen (1961), The Color of Money by Martin Scorsese, which earned him in 1987 the only Oscar out of 9 nominations.
That face through the years, was his.
Still him.
Epochs follow one another through its path.
Young people know him above all for the cult movie Slap Shot: Colpo secco by George Roy Hill (1977), in the role of Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in Mr. Hula Hoop, by the Coen brothers.
The circle had come full circle with a final role as godfather of the Irish mafia in Era mio padre, in 2003.
Unlike the greatest legends of cinema who soon abandoned the craft, Newman will remain in theaters for a long time, denouncing Hollywood in all its pomp, parties and concessions.
Bertrand Tavernier, an amateur filmmaker French, defined it, with a touch of irony, "a living challenge to underplaying", judging his performances exaggerated.
The profession was not always a game for the handsome Paul Newman, to whom roles seemed to fall like manna from heaven.
However, he often preferred the role of the outcast to that of the young actor: neurotic characters, alcoholic, carrion or desperate, of whom he expressed disarray and rebellion with his perfect traits.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown nuances of his true, modest sensibility.
Jennifer's first time, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian director Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the title role, drew a subtle female portrait of melancholy.
He, who lost his son Scott to an overdose, dedicated the film Harry and Son to him in 1984, a discreet and sad film.
Among the countless tributes rained down yesterday on Newman, his great friend and old comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had starred together in The Stangata and Butch Cassidy) said with infinite sadness "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity and love for life, two great characteristics of the late actor.
Beyond a legendary career, a great militant for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drift dies.
We will have seen her face stand out on bottles of vinegar, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging it a choice of bad taste, although born as a gag.
The income from those sales, however, went to his Foundation for Children in Difficulty.
Newman, instead of resting on his myth, chose to commit himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter saying, "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful to his good star.
Being there was a privilege."
And it was equally privileged for us to follow the path of such a clear and generous American artist.
Model citizen, therefore, and much more.
What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag & associates?
Soon, on October 8, the hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and associates will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed in the context of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from calls for tenders was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the execution of the activities through false invoices.
The state and municipal money, a total of 65 million guilders, ended up partly in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, disclosed by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from calls for tenders on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the blocks of invoices were purchased at the Józsefváros market, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue invoices, it was established among other things during the trip to the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession, he had to choose guesthouses and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for the drinks, on the model of these then the invoices were prepared to be forwarded to the calls for tenders, among others, to those of the Ministry for Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri who, according to our information, mainly drew up the reports needed to obtain funding.
One of the choices of the "study trip" of Lados was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its associates in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurateur, would not all enter the restaurant together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in summer 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later named Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal errors and content.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay there, however the invoice included 130 guests.
But the imaginative invoice compilers went too far when they pointed out Pigal Kft., which also deals with catering, whose accounts - according to the information provided to the judicial authorities - did not even include documents in the name of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, director of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately understood that they were false documents.
"On the stamp, the name and VAT number of our company were in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal reasons, the fact that according to the invoice one hundred people were accommodated, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds.
In addition, the bill was catering and their restaurant has not been in operation for some time.
The assiduous compilers of invoices did not bother to inform themselves that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only organizes trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice with cash payment trips to Hungary, which did not agree with the company's invoice policy.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included on the invoice, while the activity of travel to countries outside the European Union is exempt from VAT.
Among other things, the amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favor of the Jobb Jövőért foundation, in fact on the services offered by the company VAT must be applied at 15% and not at 25% as indicated on the invoices, moreover the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, while the invoice manufactured was handwritten.
In addition to this, the "issuers" have ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they have indicated as an activity carried out the transport of goods by road, as we learn from the procedure of the Public Prosecutor's Office, an activity that was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment advice.
In addition, due to formal defects - due to non-conforming invoice format, false stamp - it was discovered that the invoices issued in favor of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false.
The same happened in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Ground, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters also paid no attention to the fact that HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület dined there, which is why the liquidator of the company, according to our information, denied having issued that invoice.
Have issued invoices knowingly
Another group of invoice issuers are those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért for almost 4 million guilders.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
Together with Zuschlag and partners, Biogate Kft, currently in liquidation, also collaborated with Zuschlag and its partners, which in 2003 provided invoices issued for a value of about 5 million forints to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Not even movement of money because the prepared invoices were then reversed, but the associations forgot to include this aspect in their documents.
In the following group of companies issuing invoices belong those who can be connected with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized to address the general manager of the Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, which deals with fuel and motor vehicle trade.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 relating to the sale of computer equipment, worth about 18 million guilders.
According to the investigation data, the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas under liquidation since 14 September 2005 purchased these invoices.
The general manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov forwarded documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov, during the investigation, acknowledged that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the consideration was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian bricklayers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, however, none of the companies were operational, because according to the defendant they had not received work.
However, the companies were useful to him because, at the request of the co-defendant lawyer Zsolt Szente, who drafted the founding documents of the companies, invoices were issued on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to Zuschlag: Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
On behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov issued 15 invoices to the various entities for a total value of 14.2 million forints.
The prosecutor believes that Kubatov pocketed 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices, as well as VAT.
The man also used the Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, manufactured for the competition notice of Biztos Pont.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a call for the Socialist Party's public benefit organization, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 forints each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the tender.
In order to prevent this from coming to light, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These invoices were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants, as they have already done in the prosecutor's office, will probably report on the trend of invoice production.
However, the most interesting thing could be if the number one defendant, János Zuschlag, decides to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has promised several times to talk about everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
It remains to be seen whether it is in his interest, it could also be that the Socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for compensation of 50 million guilders, much of the damage - would be willing to make the scapegoat.
Zuschlag could also have been offended for now, since his requests for the alleviation of his prison conditions, i.e. the granting of house arrest, have not been met so far.
While the perpetrators of non-compensable commercial crimes and causing much greater damage can freely walk or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings against them, which is not granted to him.
The psychology of excessive licitation: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economist researchers at New York University have managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to be left behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method examined the active areas of the brains of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex comes into intensive operation when losing to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists in the research team carried out a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups litigated against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told what was the real value of the product in question and they made their bet.
To another group in addition to this they promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in case of loss at auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the winning was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Proving the neurologists hypothesis, members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control or "winning" group.
"These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, until now these explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to contact the doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The term hepatitis is the collective name for contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the alimentary canal (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against the A and B virus, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, yellowish spots form on the skin and whites of the eyes, the feces become light and urine dark, healing occurs within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most severe variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is estimated that only one in ten people receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
So it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical analyzes.
This disease is much more frequent than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed people.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth turning to the family doctor when noticing any symptoms of unknown origin.
