Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help through partial nationalization the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first to end up in difficulty in Europe due to the crisis in the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial - insurance institution with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been struggling for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard may set a precedent.
Under the decision taken Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell part of its interests, including first of all the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' shares had started with a vertical collapse, serious signs of crisis in the institute had then appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to fail.
The bank's shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, their lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current share prices, the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The top management blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the American plan of 700 billion dollars.
On Monday, the stock slowly started to rise again.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come up with a worthy offer.
The Belgian government has previously assured that investors need not fear losing money.
Among the bank's customers panic did not spread, branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing firms.
Does those who believe in God feel less pain?
According to the result of a recent survey, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have performed an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre survey, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while all of them were looking at a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The test is the first of a series of researches in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes electroshock was connected to the left hand of the experiment subject.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the seventeenth century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with an Ermine by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the fifteenth century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would originate a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to have a reassuring effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they calmed down and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they gave an account of 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but the right image must be found.
"We have to look for an image towards which they have very positive feelings, like a mother or a father" - said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it succeeds in changing our personality," Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the day of the tenth birthday Google can claim to be as much in people's pockets as in the sky above their heads; He knows where they spent their holidays, what clinic they attend and what interests him.
This, however, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, is still not enough.
What concerns skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the substance of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data from its users as possible, and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders, which was: "let's put all the information in the world into a system!"
According to the director of Google interviewed, the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt replied: he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?", but software does not know how to answer seemingly simple questions because they do not know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their internet searches exactly the searched words are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search started two years ago, users can e.g. store their browsing history, they can look at what they have searched for and clicked, these will then generate much better tailor-made results in the long run; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our preferences declared and recorded previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - ask users worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of Internet users are provoked by the fright felt by the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the sense of guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom or even for the rebellion against power.
However, one fact is confirmed, namely that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights instead sighed with relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even afterwards you can not force Google with any point in the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully snatched nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in connection with the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain individual users' search lists and the entire two-month list of web pages and keywords.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data lash out at Google because they believe that this will affect their intimate sphere and private life by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for their conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users who have appeared in numerous countries see in them the next generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft dismissed as conquering the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the package of programs is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the keywords most often repeated in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing but collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all these can enter them in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his most recent photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common circle of friends, easily learns with whom her wicked boy spent the night or a company can fire one of its employees because he wrote a sincere opinion on the top management:  One thing is certain, the concept of private life has now been completely reconsidered.
Those who live an online life make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid Google's monopoly can do so (starting for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time leaving no traces voluntarily).
There are not a few people who do not register on purpose to community pages so as not to be found, Google's online applications, from word processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far existing.
The public is secretly waiting for the moment when Google will pull out its claws.
Currently the company with its 156 billion dollars of value is worth more than IBM (140 billion dollars), Intel (124 billion dollars) or Coca Cola (110 billion dollars), the AdWords / AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the services introduced in record time instead cause great discomfort not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development companies.
However, critical observers alongside all this find alarming points: the top management, for example, has completely refused the protest of employees after doubling the company kindergarten fee, has considered the repeated daily catering of employees too expensive, but all this diminishes the fact that in 2006 Google bowed its head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter all the results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is certain, however, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world at one point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google will assume such proportions that the company will soon find itself before the American Supreme Court,  others are afraid of the Health system, in fact in this we can create our own health profile with our reports, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database may offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the story Scroogled by the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
