Intelligent machine imitates the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop collision avoidance technologies than to mimic obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example, those of bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, hornets gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic cue on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic minicar equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of avoiding all collisions.
By flying, the bees form their own oval personal space that looks a lot like our protective shield," Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development, told the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300-degree view in every direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetry laser idea to copy the bee's sight function.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor which immediately turns it into a collision avoidance command.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damageable and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must mirror what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to the bees to dodge other bees, the robot, as a possibility, can rotate on itself, speed up and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high-energy density lithium-polymer batteries, which means they last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of an immediate collision avoidance technology which, Nissan expects, can be installed in production vehicles within 10 years.
Another possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoids obstacles on the road leads to the destination.
