The written version of the $700 billion economic bailout bill for the purchase of disproportionate debts has been drafted, to be applied in several parts.
In the first step, half of the sum is spent.
In the new agreements that lasted until midnight on Saturday according to East Coast Time, congressional leaders decided on the $700 billion bailout after a debate that had lasted for days, Reuters reported.
We have made serious progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, who said that all that remained was to put the deal on paper.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, supported the compromise of the plan.
Speaking about the outcome of the compromise, Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: the programme will work and be effective, but there is still much to be done. According to Pelosi, this is not a bailout of Wall Street but a reversal of the economic bandwagon.
The written version of the plan was made public before Asian markets opened at 8 a.m. Washington time (2 a.m. on Monday Central European time), but it did not bring much stock market growth.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote first on the bill called the 2008 economic stabilization law concerning the program, after which it will be up to the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, then welcomed the news of the deal to the White House.
We are pleased with the progress achieved tonight and greatly appreciate the efforts of the two parties to stabilize our financial markets and defend the economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program, however, differs from the Bush administration's original proposal, which stipulated that the $700 billion would all be spent on the purchase of bonds with disproportionate credits behind them.
Now as a first step you can spend at most half of the sum of 700 billion dollars, 250 billion immediately after Monday's vote of Congress, with these the Treasury Department will buy securities with disproportionate credits behind it, the fate of the remaining 100 billion dollars will decide the president.
A special college will control the program in which the chairman of the Federal Reserve also participates.
The spending of the other half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury can apply a combined tactic: it can buy loans, mortgages and securities with mortgages and other types of "poisoned" credits at the same time.
The purchase can be done through auctions and directly - announced competent ministry.
The legal rule makes it possible for the companies concerned to take part in an insurance program where the Treasury guarantees the means that give concern, for which the companies will pay a price appropriate to the probable damages.
Henrz Paulson said: The law provides the means necessary for $700 billion to arrive for the urgent needs of the American monetary system, whether it is the purchase of the wrong financial means, or their insurance or to avoid the risk of the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take all necessary steps to be ready to introduce the newly signed law," he added.
The directors of banks in crisis and waiting for state aid think instead that the government will limit their good exit, defined by overseas slang simply as golden parachutes.
Payment limitations will only occur in some cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury offers the aid.
In essence, the limitation means that if the ministry buys as part of an auction, it will impose a surcharge on the golden parachute, if they do not retire the fallen bank manager.
When buying disproportionate debts directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that directors' money is not exaggerated.
To this must be added that the already existing contracts of the golden parachute will not change, the limitation is valid only for new ones to encourage participation in the program.
This is the first case in American history of a legal limitation on the remuneration of general managers, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the House of Representatives Financial Services Committee.
In addition, the state has the right to appropriate a share of the banks participating in the program, decreasing the risk of taxpayers, since in the end they can also gain if the economy, and with it the bailed out bank, gets back on its feet.
The bill includes that over the next five years the president must submit to Congress a proposal that sets out how to return to taxpayers the projected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their doubts about the project.
This is not what American citizens have asked us not to defend taxpayer dollars," said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur believes the measures were taken by the same people who are responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industry prices continue to rise
Domestic industrial sales prices in August 2008 increased by 0.1% compared to the previous month, by 12.9% compared to August 2007, according to the Hungarian Central Statistical Institute.
Industrial export sales prices in July 2008 were 1.1% higher than in July 2008, while they fell by 3.9% compared to the previous year.
As a result of the change in domestic and export prices, industrial production costs were 0.7% higher than in the previous month and 3.2% higher than in a year ago.
Domestic industrial sales prices for the previous month increased by only 0.1%.
Domestic sales prices in the processing sector also rose minimally, by 0.1%, compared to July.
The largest increase in prices in August 2008 occurred in the leather and shoe processing sector (2.8%), especially bags and belts with 4.6% and shoe production with a 2.5% monthly increase.
The high price level of plastics and chemicals caused a significant monthly increase (1.6%) in the products and chemicals sector.
A decrease in prices occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4%), in the production of electrical tools and machinery (0.9%) and to a lesser extent in woodworking (0.1%)
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices rose by between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, prices increased in August by 0.3% in domestic industrial sales, primarily as a result of the dominant effect of the authorities' increase in gas prices since 1 July.
Compared in 12 months, considering the domestic sales of the processing industry sectors, the largest increases occurred in the petroleum products processing sector (32.4%).
In the manufacture of metalworking products, prices rose by 13.2% and 11% in the production of food, beverages and tobacco, which accounted for a decisive role.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile sector (2.5%) and in the production of electrical tools and machinery (0.3%).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the rate of price increase varied from 0.6% to 9.1%.
In total, prices in the processing industry rose by 10.2% in the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7% higher than last year.
In domestic sales among target groups in the sectors, the largest increase in monthly prices occurred in August in sectors producing capital goods (0.7%).
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3%, in the energy and after-use sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month last year, the increase in the largest prices was observed in the energy and subsequent use sector (16.8%).
In the sectors producing consumer articles the increase was 6.8%, for capital goods a decrease of 1.4% was measured.
Industrial export sales prices in guilders rose in August by 1.1% compared with the previous month, compared with 12 months and decreased by 3.9%.
The Hungarian forint weakened against the euro by 1.7% against the dollar by 7.1% compared to August 2007, strengthened by 7.5% against the euro and by 15.9% against the dollar.
