The fox in the hen house
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase data, often refuse to take out an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription data of drugs depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox" - writes the Washington Post quoting Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies make the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims subject to the state of health of the possible customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not take out insurance.
Some time ago the customer had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper process 10 years ago: based on the customer's identification code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines you have purchased in the last year and a half, and from this the program shows which diseases you suffer from and what health conditions you are in.
For example, if you regularly buy large quantities of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in the blood is in practice incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer in addition to paper work does not have much left, even if small difficulties arise.
Among the cons is that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance-commercial point of view, counts as a factor of increased risk, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for patient approval.
Now the authorities oblige them to do so even though they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies lately also process the result of laboratory tests and link them to medical consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and in parallel the control of usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
Before Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control powers to companies specializing in data services.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that links data forwarding with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much refuse approval because otherwise the insurers do not conclude the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
