Mp3 players under accusation, put your hearing at risk
Listening to loud music for a prolonged period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is according to the European Commission, which in a statement released in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU's Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSRSERI), published today.
"From this scientific opinion - reads the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability".
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high hearing levels may unconsciously damage their hearing beyond repair," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings - continues the EU manager - a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific advice, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
"The scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music equipment and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to these noise sources.
This damage can be greatly limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment if they listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limits on the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
