Elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the rescue plan of 700 billion dollars launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times informing us that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington' and the world of finance,  strong especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, that has become overwhelmingly alive with the vote I mentioned at the beginning.
However, this is just an example of the changes, of the great changes, that the current economic earthquake perhaps heralds or already allows us to see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of phenomena in incubation for some time that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary relaunch, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, close ties with foreign countries, but which first of all involve to a very large extent the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, by the way, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the game or does not have much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which, divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies, fails to decide on any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when it comes to the corners it is only the States that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back on track.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal to an increasing extent with those very little immaterial things that are water,  Crops, oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So those who find themselves sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty which, however, presages a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request for someone who knows how to take matters into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, especially economic ones, which proved to be so inadequate and full of gray areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an impatience, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is, it seems to be gaining ground, in large sectors of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have done their time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, underground feeds a ramified but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of recent and very recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory).  of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
One gets the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats someone would say, are increasingly struggling to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating,  It increases, it potentially shakes out of proportion.
In the face of all this, to speak of a 'rebellion of the masses' on the agenda would frankly be exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open certainly isn't open at all.
The superglue to walk on walls
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on walls like Spiderman.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come very close.
With an adhesive of only 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a body of 100 kilograms glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team is an evolution of existing ones that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of noodles," says Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that can ensure perfect adherence to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "easily detaches from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
WALKING ON WALLS? "This material could be useful as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls just like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
For the moment no superheroes.
The University of California, Berkeley, is also researching a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, the Californian scholars presented an adhesive formed by microfibers like hair that cleans itself of dust during movement on a surface to always maintain a perfect adherence.
Drugs: never with fruit juices
Pay attention to grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if taken at the same time as some life-saving drugs alter their absorption amplifying or decreasing depending on the effectiveness with serious consequences for health.
To reiterate the risks of both packaged and fresh fruit juices associated with the intake of some medicines David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, who from the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia launches a new alarm: just a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice to reduce the absorption of some life-saving drugs,  canceling the beneficial effects and putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice had already come under fire because it was considered responsible for increasing the effects of some antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antihistamine and neurological medicines to levels considered toxic.
DRUGS AT RISK - The same Italian Medicines Agency had given news in an information bulletin two years ago warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what you drink if you take drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to experts, orange and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit drugs.
Along the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department of the State University of Milan: "These discoveries are generally immediately reported to the various international and national drug agencies that eventually change the information notes of the drugs.
So always read the package inserts of the medicines you take and if there is something that is not clear to us, do not be impressed but ask for clarification from the doctor or pharmacist » underlined the expert to the Ansa agency.
The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his studies on trade patterns and the localization of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is a well-known columnist for the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the main critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy choices.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, in the days when Enron failed, Krugman predicted in an editorial published in the New York Times that the second event would be more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences for the history of the United States.
A prediction that sparked quite a few controversies and that for years was reproached to the economist, but which has now proved to be correct.
"I'm surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals like the collapse of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from public attention," Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the Executive Board of the European Central Bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value", but also a popularizer with a "very aggressive" style, particularly critical of the excesses of liberalism of the Bush administration.
Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package»
It is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the better known Microsoft Office.
After a work of almost a year by volunteer developers, behind whom SUN Microsystem watches, the new Open Office shows itself to the general public with several new features: to the welcome screen and the revised interface made less spartan, other more substantial ones are added such as native compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format,  the latest ISO standard version.
Attention also paid to interoperability with the Office suite 2007, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting some specific features of some modules such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example to send them by e-mail, or the ability to import PDF files into the graphic processing module, preserving the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front you can create "hybrid PDF" documents, which combine the typical graphics of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a word processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received several improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet you can intervene with several hands between different users, avoiding conflicts on changes, in the word processor, each collaborator is assigned a color in the comments for better recognition during revision.
Some companies are also working to bring some OpenOffice features to the web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they are expected to release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and has been added to the English one that was on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can also be sent to your home or workplace.
And if the theme of gratuitousness can be a driving force for the diffusion in homes, it is precisely in the business environment that Open Office the suite tries the big bet, already being able to count on several projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
And there are also companies that offer an ideal training, consulting and assistance service for small and medium-sized companies, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for word processing equivalent to Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for Powerpoint emulation presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the most famous Access is the program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, is finally the graphic module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today we are almost 3 million and 600 thousand, with the release of the new version it is likely that we can even exceed the expected figure.
