Found the plane of Steve Fossett the billionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at 3000 meters above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
The sheriff of Madeira County, John Anderson, dispelled the doubts that still remained: "The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is precisely what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff then specified that no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was presumed dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Transportation Safety (NTSB) said that a few hours after the sighting of the wreckage, a team of investigators was sent, who then identified the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with Fossett's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
The search for Fossett was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete a round-the-world balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he went around the world by plane and non-stop.
Among his many records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
