Students victims of high rents up to 900 euros for a room
The rental market for university students knows no crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now assumed very serious characters to the point of excluding entire groups of young people from the right to study for the very high overall costs that the families of origin should bear - explains the head of the Sunia study office, Laura Mariani - in these cities the strong demand from students has so deformed the market as to trigger a process of generalized increase also for residents".
In most cases, rental offers contain a series of violations: free contracts, unregistered, without rent limit, linked sub-leases.
For the Sunia extraordinary interventions are necessary that, through the revision of taxation, can control prices.
Looking at the detail of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room it ranges from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in the Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) about 600 euros are asked for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double room.
Values only slightly lower (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You save only if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed you need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they carry a greater weight in the city's economy.
In cities where the phenomenon of rents to non-EU students is more frequent, such as Perugia, there is a further anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% of the rent asked to foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historic cinemas
Historic cinemas close in favor of Multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the suburbs of large multiplexes and the consequent death by consumption of single-screen cinemas in the central areas of cities, is one of those events that seem inevitable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places full of memory, "it is as if a friend was missing, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Jury Prize of Cannes,  and that told the poetry of a provincial cinema and the nostalgia for a way of living the cinema lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed their doors, and to pay the greatest price are above all the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna stands out with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the highest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but we should guarantee the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of allocation for the fund in favor of merchants: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is ethically and morally shameful that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be needed to support the sector."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, has decided to run for cover with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-screen cinemas both in the historic center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules envisaged there are tax relief measures in favor of managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic zone and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
«It is an initiative that I like» observes Giuseppe Tornatore «and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counteract the overwhelming power of multiplexes, traditional cinemas must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale in Via Nazionale now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, so as not to see the billboards blackened by dust I turn the other way».
Links between politics and 'ndrangheta arrested mayor of Gioia Tauro
