When energy is born from the waves, now the big names take the field
It is an endless field, which occupies over 70% of the surface of the planet and now the great world energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have set their eyes, and now try to get their hands, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental demands and the new increase in oil are boosting the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be covered by plants to exploit the wave motion of the seas.
This amount would be twice that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And in addition there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more are betting on marine energy and among these companies that have always been devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesman of a subsidiary company of the US oil giant to the Wall Street Journal business newspaper - and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is no small sign, especially considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to travel the path of energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate according to observers a rising interest.
Technology to be fine-tuned.
Experts speak of a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not dispel all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which makes the buoys move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure spins a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now, there are four such plants being planned, awaiting only federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the turbine blades to turn, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others bordering the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments of up to 35 million for 2009.
